{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17624126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17624126"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:15:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:15:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16890"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16890"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.58,0.21,0.13,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9580"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67873"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9580","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9580"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16890"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53338"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5141"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22606"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22612"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22726"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67873","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67873"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to a pharmacy requesting treatment for diarrhoea that started 12 hours ago. She has had four loose stools but is otherwise well with no fever, blood in stool, or abdominal pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELoperamide is a medication that can be purchased over-the-counter without a prescription. Both the pharmacist and the purchaser need to be aware of situations where its use alone might not be appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following situations would be most appropriate for the use of this agent?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute ulcerative colitis flare","Acute watery diarrhoea without systemic symptoms","Bloody diarrhoea with fever","Chronic diarrhoea of unknown cause","Infectious gastroenteritis in infants"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute watery diarrhoea without systemic symptoms\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary indication for loperamide use. The medication provides symptomatic relief by reducing intestinal motility in cases of uncomplicated diarrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent contraindications or inappropriate uses:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBloody diarrhoea with fevers\u003C/strong\u003E suggests invasive infection where anti-motility agents may be harmful. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic diarrhoea of unknown cause\u003C/strong\u003E requires investigation to determine the underlying cause before symptomatic treatment. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute ulcerative colitis flare\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect; anti-motility agents are contraindicated in inflammatory bowel disease as they may precipitate toxic megacolon. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfectious gastroenteritis in infants\u003C/strong\u003E is also incorrect, as loperamide is contraindicated in young children due to risk of respiratory depression and paralytic ileus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen using loperamide, patients should be advised to maintain adequate fluid intake and seek medical attention if symptoms persist beyond 48 hours or if they develop fever, bloody stools, or severe abdominal pain.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Loperamide is indicated for acute diarrhoea without signs of systemic illness or invasive infection.","Loperamide should not be used in inflammatory bowel disease, infectious diarrhoea with blood or fever, or in children under 4 years.","Loperamide provides symptomatic relief only and should not delay investigation of chronic diarrhoea."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53338"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16890"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53338"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T16:08:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T16:09:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9580"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67873"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\ud